\begin_layout Section
Batch Normalization (30%)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Batch Normalization (BN) is a widely adopted technique that enables faster and more stable training of deep neural networks (DNNs).
 The tendency to improve accuracy and speed up training have established BN as a favorite technique in deep learning.
 At a high level,
 BN is a technique that aims to improve the training of neural networks by stabilizing the distributions of layer inputs.
 This is achieved by introducing additional network layers that control the first two moments (mean and variance) of these distributions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this project,
 you will first test the effectiveness of BN in the training process,
 and then explore how does BN help optimization.
 The sample codes are provided by Python.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
The Batch Normalization Algorithm
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Here we primarily consider BN for convolutional neural networks.
 Both the input and output of a BN layer are four dimensional tensors,
 which we refer to as 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{b,c,x,y}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $O_{b,c,x,y}$
\end_inset

,
 respectively.
 The dimensions corresponding to examples within a batch 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

,
 channel 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

,
 and two spatial dimensions 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y$
\end_inset

 respectively.
 For input images the channels correspond to the RGB channels.
 BN applies the same normalization for all activations in a given channel,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
O_{b,c,x,y}\leftarrow\gamma_{c}\frac{I_{b,c,x,y}-\mu_{c}}{\sqrt{\sigma^{2}_{c}+\epsilon}}+\beta_{c}\text{\ensuremath{\qquad}}\forall b,c,x,y.
\]

\end_inset

Here,
 BN subtracts the mean activation 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{c}=\frac{1}{\left|\mathcal{\mathcal{B}}\right|}\sum_{b,x,y}I_{b,c,x,y}$
\end_inset

from all input activations in channel 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

,
 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{B}$
\end_inset

 contains all activations in channel 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 across all features 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 in the entire mini-batch and all spatial 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y$
\end_inset

,
 locations.
 Subsequently,
 BN divides the centered activation by the standard deviation 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{c}$
\end_inset

 (plus 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon$
\end_inset

 for numerical stability) which is calculated analogously.
 During testing,
 running averages of the mean and variances are used.
 Normalization is followed by a channel-wise affine transformation parametrized through 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{c},\beta_{c}$
\end_inset

,
 which are learned during training.
\end_layout

